[[<]]
Many, //many// years passed before the Altruist-9 finally made contact with EE-00059's location, which appeared, at least at first, to be a large waste of a time and resources. Not to mention the collective economy of a few small but once prosperous countries and city-states, as is the way such projects were. 

The probe that had endured this journey considered these factors very little. It wasn't burdened by such trivial qualms, instead focused entirely on the mission and its completion. If nothing were there when it reached its destination, as long as it could report that information and said information would reach Earth eventually, then all was a success. 

The chassis of Altruist-9 glimmered as it sat within the endless sky, scanning the area with billion-dollar sensors, floating idly in the far reaches of deep space. Picturesque in juxtaposition, a feat of human engineering surrounded by stars on all sides. 

It didn't take long for the stillness of everything to be interrupted by a sudden and unexplained shimmer, accompanied by a faint sound akin to tearing paper. It started near the probe, expanding outward in two directions on an axis until it was massive in size, a great disk of light within void, presenting itself to the humble emissary. EE-00059-1. The wormhole. Altruist-9 took note of this development, unfazed, measuring equipment detecting nothing unusual, despite how unusual that was in its own right.

A few moments later, the quaint machine released a small spheroid device from a slot on its exterior, which expanded and flattened simultaneously into a wide disk. A few status lights flashed, changing from red, to yellow, and finally a steady green. Then, the probe transfered the data it had collected on the surrounding environment towards this disk, which it then beamed out, towards a series of entangled relay probes of similar design released during traversal. Satisfied, the Altruist-9 turned towards the glowing doorway to its right.

Upon piloting itself past the shrinking threshold, as it approached a 6th-dimensional manifold at EE-00059-1's epicenter with increasing velocity, the probe witnessed an experience that defied words. It happened briefly, in a moment, and then passed like a dream. Nothing else could be said about it.

Not long after, the Altruist-9 would deliver its payload of Earthly human information, along with a single drone containing an advanced artificially-intelligent conscript known as "Buddy.aic" to the only planet remotely close to the wormhole.

Buddy is a six-legged, arthropod-structured drone capable of observing, storing, and relaying information for Foundation analysis. It has been specialized in problem solving scenarios and thus is ideal for dynamic, unknown environments. It's also somewhat of a know-it-all.

Unfortunately, all transmissions with Buddy.aic were lost upon its traversal into EE-00059-1. It was expected, and technology capable of returning transport of similar probes was generally assumed to be absent on the opposite side of the anomaly.

This was not really the case.

Advanced technologies like this had existed for one-and-a-half billion years on the opposite side of EE-00059-1. Finding someone that gave a shit, however, could be a challenge.

The wormhole whose other end was termed EE-00059-1 ejected plenty of debris from other worlds. Things on the far sides of the gateway would try (and fail) to communicate with the trillions of lifeforms that resided and died on the modest sphere of beige rapidly approaching Buddy.aic as it fell from the sky.

The Altruist was no more, but the sentiment of its namesake remained within the core of the small drone. It was here to help, and the organisms living on the world below needed it as much as anyone could.

Although the people of modern-day "Earth", lost in their own comfort, would never learn the full story about the destruction of their home planet, the loss of contact and subsequent repopulation of humanity's other half was complete. Among those who survived in this neck of the woods, stories of what had happened would be passed down with significant recall and verisimilitude that most could recite with ease. It was, after all, their legacy that brought them there, and their anomalous roots that sustained them.

On this end of a strange Ellis-Einstein-Rosen white wormhole, whose threshold hovered permanently in the skies above and whose other end only opened when it was necessary, there existed a scorched planet of dust and deserts. It orbited a peculiar and persistent blackbody sun that, while quite dim, would burn the eyes of any living being even remotely squinting at its surface. At the time of arrival for its current inhabitants, this didn't matter. 

The ancient proto-human race was about to come to an abrupt and untimely end due to a very well-aimed rogue star, having been thrown by an angry and jealous god in the direction of Earth Prime. Despite all odds, the species managed to preserve a small fraction of itself in the wake of annihilation, stowed aboard two generation ships capable of hopping to various phase spaces in a desperate plea to locate a suitable new home for the many sleeping individuals found aboard these vessels. 

Unfortunately, the loss of the human homeworld was as big of a failure for the one who committed the act as it was a tragic loss for its previous inhabitants. The entity desired extermination, not simple displacement, and thus eventually decided to be more //direct// in fulfilling these desires. 

The two ships were thus accosted by this foul interloper time and time again, the ships hopping to new places as soon as they were found. It wasn't until they were separated that this entity let them be. Neither knew why for sure, but they both considered separately the possibility that it was simply twice the work that had halved its motivation to wipe them out.

New Earth would go on to be mostly successful, almost burning itself out on multiple occasions (and **definitely** on certain timelines, but we won't get into that), and the folks of the nameless desert planet once thought to be a temporary home would be none the wiser. Civilizations would rise and fall, Earthly paradigms would shift constantly over millennia. History wrote and rewrote itself many times, leading to the aforementioned ignorance.

The lost half, while free from both the evils of the universe and the Foundation, as they knew it,  learned to live and rely solely on one another. It was necessary. The lack of outside interests meant an era of peace and historical continuity that would go on to solidify their residence on that planet, holed up in the shimmering megastructure whose name translated roughly to "The Stack".

It was named such for being immeasurably high and //fucking cramped.// Atmospheric regions on the surface planet were pretty hot on one side, melting the flesh off most things that dared to walk about during the perpetual, shadowy daytime of the tidally-locked planet. The Stack was located on the comparatively cooler side, and had grown to be loved and hated by its residents who had no choice but to live out their days on their lonely new home.

The megalithic complex was built from most of the wreckage that didn't completely burn up on its way onto the surface of the planet, expanded with metals derived from shallow veins and various silicates that were in no short supply. It was a hodgepodge, yet tightly wound community of beings that had little to do other than survive and occasionally eat one another if it came to it.

It was miserable to say the least, with brief periods of beauty and wonder that broke free of the monotony of their daily lives. People inside the walls were kept sheltered from the oppressive rays on the outside, venturing into the wastes to haul debris and tumor-laden corpses in suits that only allowed first degree burns for their occupants. It wasn't much, but it was enough.

Similarly, when the Altruist-9 had entered the nearby wormhole, its outer structure wasn't much,  but just enough to withstand the immense forces within. The fuselage was essentially annihilated on the way through, but that was alright; its payload was covered in a thick, resilient paste of exotic matter that resembled raspberry jam but tasted like formaldehyde and could strip paint off of most cars. Buddy was unfazed by all of this because it was what you would call a cold, unfeeling machine. 

Buddy.aic's red-tinged canister landed not-too-softly on the surface of the desert planet in a plume of dust and sand, a few kilometers outside the grey-silver walls of the Stack. After initial readings of the atmosphere, it was revealed to be nitrogen-rich, but lacked oxygen completely. Buddy.aic noted that it wouldn't be rusting any time soon and began meandering about in the general direction of the distant structure with intent to find something new and exciting to report back home, once it figured out how to do that.
