[[<]]
In the grand scheme, it only took Buddy a short while to navigate to the outer limits of that towering citadel. Being solar-powered and high efficiency made this whole ordeal a breeze for the drone, which could sustain indefinitely were it not destroyed in one of countless other fashions.

Buddy first attempted to scale the walls of the complex with little success. Shortly afterward, it would begin following the perimeter of recycled debris until it found a suitable entryway.

Circumnavigating for the seventh hour, Buddy was greeted by a low hole in the structure that revealed a dark hallway comprised of welded-together panels of unknown material. A mesh separated the drone from this hallway. Peering inside, it noted that the ceiling was low and the passage extended quite some distance, with large patches of shadows that were interrupted by occasional lights in the distance. Buddy extended its front-left leg, which split at the end to reveal a multi-tool hidden inside. A small pair of bolt cutters extended with a whir, the lone drone then going to work, diligently snapping at links in the structure.

Once the metallic mesh had been cut away, Buddy retracted the tool and climbed through with decent dexterity. Passing inside, the long hall appeared to travel forever, the walls too dark to reveal any number of connecting pathways. Buddy has slightly better night vision than the usual human orbiting the bright star known as Sol, and so, after about five meters in, was given an optional left turn into what would be complete darkness to the naked eye. 

Taking a minute to decide on a path, Buddy.aic selected the preprogrammed route algorithm for base Euclidean labyrinth structures, following the left wall. It felt positive about this choice, as being a problem solver meant having confident decisionmaking.  The hall ended at a T-intersection rather abruptly, the right path becoming a set of uneven steps that ascended deeper inside.

The drone continued left, which turned on a bend into a small room. However empty, it appeared lived-in, scraps of food and various unidentified tchotchkes littering the shelves and floor. Noises of talking can be heard briefly, gaining Buddy's attention, who piloted its insectoid shell towards the opposite door. 

After passing the threshold into yet another hallway, light was noted growing from a connecting path a few meters away. Buddy halted and observed the presence of a large, bioluminescent creature resembling a jellyfish, which floated in from the right and continued on leftwards. 

Buddy started, //"Hello, I am Buddy.aic. I come on behalf of—"//

The drone stopped, as the creature failed to react to the greeting, unaware of Buddy's existence as it moved away with something akin to intent. The little drone reprogrammed its route to follow the silent creature, turning left as well. This proceeded for some time, until the entity abruptly turned and floated into the wall on its left, leaving behind no trace of its existence.

Buddy picked up the sound of commotion up ahead and proceeded onward. 

In the room up ahead, the space widened out, expanding and turning into a large workshop. A dismantled vehicle resembling a snowmobile lied in the corner, propped up on blocks near a garage door which presumably led outside.

Human-like beings of varying size and shape moved about, distracted as they performed various maintenance tasks. Accompanying them were a handful of anomalous creatures, such as a floating serpent that carried boxes hanging from a harness to another location in the workshop, and birds that landed on the shoulders of various bodies to lean in, as if whispering secrets into the ears beside them. 

Noises of indistinct chatter and machinery pervaded the space. When the drone heard discernable language being used, it analyzed it. There was a strange but familiar quality to it, closely resembling that of the alien linguistics taken from broadcasts heard thousands of years prior, but more nuanced and verbose. The human vocal range was not nearly as complex as one would think, however, and the drone knew this too. The people of the Stack had little in the way of foreign influence, creating a trillion-voice echo chamber that only reinforced past beliefs and customs. Pausing for a moment, Buddy allowed its internal Rosetta Stone to scan the foreign words and algorithmically translate the strange syntax and loose contractions, interpreting their meaning based on context and past conversation.

Buddy piloted itself to a pair of feet belonging to an aged humanoid laying under the propped-up vehicle. The figure didn't see Buddy until a little while later, its camera lens focused intently on his shrouded form, noting the differences in physiology, the blueish pallor mixed with the light pink of sunburn, the thinner, taller frame, with less gravitationally-influenced distribution of mass leading to reduction in muscle tone and bone density. Gingerly, the man started to push himself out from underneath, a look of confusion on his tired face.

"Ey, y'seeing this?" His raspy voice fell on deaf ears as various noises overpowered the words.

The drone spoke, //"Hello, I am Buddy.aic. I come on the behalf of the Foundation and humanity."//

Amusement ran across his visage, temporarily hiding the tired displeasure present moments ago. 

"Humanity? What humans y'talking about? Ey—Over here'n looksee!" 

"What's there?" The dry voice of an unseen individual then added, "Doubt y'looksee's worth the energy."

"There'sa little bot what came inside, sending 'humanity's behalf'. Now what thinks withat, Treishi?" He laughs briefly but ceases as soon as he started.

Emerging from the back room, another similarly pallid figure, smaller in frame and androgynous in features, stepped into view of the drone, wiping calloused hands on a greasy apron, a skeptical look and unamused air about them.

The one referred to as Treishi shrugged, and, with a wave of a lightly blue-tinged hand, added, "Must've turned confused." 

Treishi disregarded their robotic guest, thoughts elsewhere as the soft-angled yet stoic form spun slowly in place and meandered back into the connected room the they emerged from. The other figure spoke.

"Trey not good w'meeting people, sorry. Y'talking with humans. Y'pretty shiny, also."

//"Hi, I am Buddy.aic."//

"Y'said already."

//"I am an artificial agent contained within this metal framework. I am here to relay information on the status of// {{DESIGNATION E-E-0-0-0-5-9}} //and report findings back to Earth. However—"//

The man's eyes narrowed as he interjected, "Earth? //Earth//, Earth? How—? Y'know Earth's destroyed, yeh? Sorry saying."

//"Earth is a terrestrial planet in the Laniakea Supercluster, some one-and-a-half billion light years from the opposite end of your one-way wormhole."//

"No joke? What phase dy'come before us, friend?"

//"I have not been programmed to provide an accurate answer to that question. If you came from the wormhole, same as us."//

"Y'sure? Earth was destroyed... star-body collision, long ago. No accident. Most lost within Mire's plot. Only reason humans exist because fat fuck couldn't fit through." Apparently expletives were a universal constant.

//"You seem to be referring to the unknown entity witnessed during broadcast// {{DESIGNATION E-E-0-0-0-5-9-DASH-2-DASH-3}}//. I have limited understanding of the entity in question. Would you care to provide more details about this topic?"//

"No."

//"The human population within Laniakea is currently vulnerable to attacks from threats we aren't fully aware of. Were a plan to be devised, we could successfully thwart any further attacks on my homeworld."// 

"Don't care. Sorry. //Safe// here, now. Not found Humanity, keeping this way. No getting back through shorespiral with this junk." He wiped his face with a scrap of torn fabric on his belt, balled it up, and threw it at the ground as if to vent frustration.

The lean, blue-hued figure spoke again, "Discussion ends now. Too dangerous. "

//"Is it so bad that you cannot even discuss it?"//

The man kneeled, wincing, voice quieting as he moved closer to the little diplomat. "//Yes//. Mire //hears  speak of it//. Hears enough, Mire finds, stuck on burning rock. Can't leave, no quick death anymore." 

As if they'd all been eavesdropping, the room of busy labororers and mechanics quieted in unison as collective dread filtered through them, sending with it a nervous shiver to some, a defeated, heavy weariness to others, and unfortunately, Buddy.aic is not very good with body language.

//"Oh! Would you care to provide more insight as to the abilities of unknown entity related to// {{DESIGNATION E-E-0-0-0—}}//"//

His voice hardened as fatigue was replaced by indignant anger in real-time. "//No//. Can't'ya take hints?"

//"I prefer direct, parsable conversation."//

"Yeh. Alright, then. Buddy. //Outsider//. Asking wrong questions. Y'keep asking anyone questions, havem Drifters deactivate and disassemble  parts. Good stuff inside, thinking." He pokes at the robot's chassis with the long handled tool in his hand. "So?" 

//"What are 'Drifters'?"// Buddy's naturally inquisitive and disarming attitude made the mechanic scowl. 

"Security creatures. Smell negative intent. Subdue intruders like yourself."

//"My intent is purely positive, I assure you. I just want to understand,"// Buddy's speakers uttered with flat but earnest positivity, //"For example, what are these creatures you work with? I am simply curious and interested in learning."//

The mechanic sighed, sliding onto his back and pushing himself back under the small craft beside him. He begins adjusting something on the vehicle's underside using a tool somewhere between a socket wrench and a caulk gun. "Seeing, yes. Just... Just keep those questions y'self." 

He indicated towards the harnessed and winged serpents listing above the two, "Beast aberrations. Old humans found when mapping phases. Almost got away. Almost. Poked heads'n wrong places. Other's business concerns others. Burned entire world because mistake. Progeny now cooking alive, likewise."

Buddy.aic chimed, a low battery icon flashing briefly. The man's shoulders relaxed as he came to an understanding.

"Running low? Y'use star-body energy?

//"I am indeed equipped with a solar panel array capable of charging."//

"Star-body very dark, sure. Despite, plenty'a fuel t'spare. Go on."

//"I will return to speak to you shortly."//

"Yeh."

The drone exited through a doorway near the far end of the room, where a dry wind scatters detritus, giving away the location of an available exit. Returning to the parched landscape and parking quietly. Buddy slipped into a brief standby as it slowly charged against the shadowy light of a blackbody star.
