They didn't understand it. Why they //had// to die. They probably never will.

Panning across space and time, searching forwards, backwards, up and down, left and right, the Mire, as they called it, was growing restless. Not much had happened in the last few eons, but that didn't stop the formless entity from being quite jaded about the whole ordeal.

Many years ago, prior to and upon waking from near-endless slumber, a sharp pain wracking its being, the dark entity had been a decently nice deity. Cordial. Certainly not homicidal. Back then it didn't really dislike much. Didn't do anything at all, actually. The Voidbringer was perfectly content with playing its part, occupying and managing the spaces-between-spaces in peaceful tranquility.

But then those //goddamn humans// came about. 

Back in the day, humans were nothing but your average household parasite, sucking the life out of one planet and moving on to the next with a woe-is-me look on their face. They developed this //thing// where they believed they were special, that they were the ultimate owners of the universe. 

Nothing owns the universe. Not anymore.

It was nothing personal. In the end of the day, they would have to die. That is how life works. It just needed to be done a little ahead of schedule. The human population was expanding at an alarming rate, and you would not believe how much of an issue that would become. 

No one would go as far as to say that the universe they all lived and died within was a simulation, or a computer program, or anything like that, despite evidence to the contrary. What the being would say, if it had the patience to explain, was that whatever this place was, it was one of many, and the space that contained them all was finite. It had its limits, and the shrouded entity was the first to see how those limits put strain on the framework of the system itself.

It all started with that abrupt awakening. The Emperor felt pain unlike anything experienced before as one side of the thick film that enveloped existence writhed and split along an edge, invisible needle-thin cracks that passed through the Void like it was a block of solid glass. It made its way to the other side, into the Real, glancing along its history and topology a few too many times. In the wake of that moment of moments, there existed the little black dots--a point in spacetime, every so often. Miniscule holes where there was //nothing//. A true emptiness, one that makes the empty regions of space look full and luminescent. The Lacking.

After some amount of time had passed (as far as that can be applied to something outside of temporal existence), the sudden damage endured by abstract firmament was approached and assessed. Those webbed fractures hadn't shattered the Barrier, instantaneously annihilating everything and everyone. They were but small gaps in a wall that separated someplace very different from here, and nothing more.

The [[[deleted|reconstituted]]] mass of limbs and identities on the other side did not hold the same apathy as the dark being that peered blindly at a realm not its own, one like a mirror, with large oceans of shadow interrupted by patches of pure white. Not long after, both parties realized, separately, that the fault would not close. 

An unknown time later, the two looked in unlikely kinship between the space-between-spaces and saw that the hairline fractures had grown by several orders of magnitude. Each fraction of timespace that was peeled apart represented flays on the unseen flesh of the Void Emperor.  A few millennia later, the Lacking had devoured its first galaxy. The conglomerate across the unwanted threshold glanced along the great abyss separating them from their interlocutor, who looked back and understood. The Barrier was thinning. 

That was when the ancient body known as the Mire would begin to fulfill its purpose, starting with a celestial curveball which rendered humanity to fragments. The cracks began to heal, but stopped before long; the humans had survived. 

It wasn't enough, but it was a start. Still, the Emperor mourned the loss of Earth Prime, or just Earth as it was known then. It was a magnificent display of the talents of the one who made this place, that nameless, faceless thing the Darkdweller saw twice in its short life of how-ever-many billions of years. It was once a world lush with //life// and //value//, the two things humans love most of all. Themselves, and things for themselves.  

The ships, on the other hand, were weak and ugly. They were built hastily, under duress, patched up with anomalous materials and prestidigitations. It would take very little effort to rend them into nothing. The Emperor just needed to find out where they went.

You might be asking yourself, "How did these humans, forever in their infinite glory, tie in with the thing on the opposite side of the universe, slowly taking it away?"

The world-eater, the lack-of-things. It was a sign that all the processing power in the universe just //wasn't enough//. You think making a galaxy is hard? Rotating bodies in space can be simulated on a calculator. But minds? Minds require //finesse//, require individuality and a complexity that far exceeded that of the rest of the world around it.

Something like this is fine in small amounts, in moderation, but humans are not a species known for their restraint. They've multiplied exponentially and now 90% of the processing power of the multiverse pointed down on the human experience, and they continued to spread, unabated. 

A second and third tear formed over the next few thousand millennia, fresh lacerations on the back of the Emperor, who grew ever-spiteful of the ill-fated humans.    

They were the problem child and always will be. They would be the undoing of everything. They had to be stopped. 

The Voidbringer shivered in sickly nostalgia. Many millions of years had passed by since that day when the Humans and their faceless foe came into contact last. The being roused itself from deep slumber with another sharp pain in the entire self, signaling the growth of a malignance with questionable prognosis.  How long could this place hold out before the barricades failed and the cascade of Eternity came crashing down upon them?

The Emperor heard something in the distance, a far-off pair of scissors slicing through ribbons of spacetime. It was a familiar sound, but there was something unique this time, new sounds within the sound. Talking. //Humans// talking. They were staring into the Void as it stared back, unyielding and strange. They couldn't hear the third noise, because it [[[SCP-3930|didn't exist]]].

The Void was screaming. The agony resonated in perfect harmony, creating a beacon that alerted The Emperor to its exact location. The ancient entity folded the fabric of reality, creating a series of wormholes that pointed to a peculiar blue sphere among the desolation of space, gateways surrounded by concentric rings, the edges of a dozen spacetimes incomprehensibly distant from one another.

The one they called the Mire stretched itself thin, passing through manifolds with newfound determination.

It would finish what it started. It would set things right. It was necessary.

And they would never understand that. 

